- More than friendly, would you say?

1618
01:43:35,609 --> 01:43:38,339
- I thought so.
- Why did you think so?

1619
01:43:38,445 --> 01:43:41,471
She'd kind of lean on him.

1620
01:43:41,582 --> 01:43:43,482
A couple of times she bumped him
with her hip.

1621
01:43:45,252 --> 01:43:49,211
Would you say that Mrs. Manion
was making a play for Barney Quill?

1622
01:43:49,323 --> 01:43:53,054
Objection. That calls for an assumption
on the part of the witness.

1623
01:43:53,160 --> 01:43:55,560
I withdraw the question.
Would you say...

1624
01:43:55,662 --> 01:43:58,358
Mrs. Manion was free and easy
with Barney Quill?

1625
01:43:58,465 --> 01:44:00,490
- I would.
- Your witness.

1626
01:44:00,601 --> 01:44:02,068
Mr. Paquette...

1627
01:44:02,169 --> 01:44:06,003
the attorney for the people
asked you if Mrs. Manion was "tight"...

1628
01:44:06,106 --> 01:44:08,540
and you said
that she was "high."

1629
01:44:08,642 --> 01:44:12,703
Now, speaking as a bartender,
what's the distinction between the two?

1630
01:44:12,813 --> 01:44:17,113
- I don't understand.
- When we say a person's "tight"...

1631
01:44:17,217 --> 01:44:21,586
we usually mean they're a little stupid
with the drink, isn't that so?

1632
01:44:21,688 --> 01:44:23,553
I guess so.

1633
01:44:23,657 --> 01:44:27,491
And if they're "high"
they're gay and enjoying themselves.

1634
01:44:27,594 --> 01:44:29,858
In other words,
Mrs. Manion was happy.

1635
01:44:29,963 --> 01:44:32,397
Is there anything wrong with being happy
in Thunder Bay Inn?

1636
01:44:32,499 --> 01:44:33,557
No.

1637
01:44:33,667 --> 01:44:36,500
Thunder Bay itself is a resort,
isn't it?

1638
01:44:36,603 --> 01:44:39,766
- Swimming, fishing, that sort of thing.
- Yes.

1639
01:44:39,873 --> 01:44:43,138
Is there anything unusual about seeing
a barefooted woman in Thunder Bay?

1640
01:44:43,243 --> 01:44:44,471
No.

1641
01:44:44,578 --> 01:44:47,069
So Mrs. Manion's taking her shoes off
in Thunder Bay...

1642
01:44:47,180 --> 01:44:50,240
that doesn't mean
she's being unladylike, does it?

1643
01:44:50,350 --> 01:44:52,250
- I guess not.
- Yes or no?

1644
01:44:52,352 --> 01:44:53,751
No!

1645
01:44:55,555 --> 01:45:00,288
Now, you testified that
Mrs. Manion was squealing...

1646
01:45:00,394 --> 01:45:03,295
and jumping up and down...

1647
01:45:03,397 --> 01:45:06,059
and swishing her... I think that
was the expression you used...

1648
01:45:06,166 --> 01:45:08,532
swishing her hips
around the pinball machine.

1649
01:45:08,635 --> 01:45:12,503
Now, was she creating a disturbance?
Was she attracting a crowd?

1650
01:45:12,606 --> 01:45:15,871
Were the men at the bar all
standing around watching Mrs. Manion?

1651
01:45:15,976 --> 01:45:18,501
- No.
- But you were very conscious of her.

1652
01:45:18,612 --> 01:45:21,274
Conscious enough so that you can tell us
all about her actions?

1653
01:45:21,381 --> 01:45:23,281
- Yes.
- And certainly Barney Quill...

1654
01:45:23,383 --> 01:45:27,376
he was conscious of her because
he was playing pinball with her, right?

1655
01:45:27,487 --> 01:45:31,514
So it seems that only you
and Barney Quill were acutely aware...

1656
01:45:31,625 --> 01:45:34,924
of Mrs. Manion and her actions
and her appearance.

1657
01:45:35,028 --> 01:45:37,656
Maybe good old Barney when he came up
to get some drinks from you...

1658
01:45:37,764 --> 01:45:42,167
maybe he winked and said, "Alphonse,
I'm gonna take this babe and rape her."

1659
01:45:42,269 --> 01:45:44,328
- No, he didn't.
- Maybe you said...

1660
01:45:44,438 --> 01:45:46,338
"Do it once for me, boss."

1661
01:45:46,440 --> 01:45:48,431
Objection.

1662
01:45:48,542 --> 01:45:51,102
No more questions!

1663
01:45:51,211 --> 01:45:55,147
The court's had about all of this
dogfight it can take for one day.

1664
01:45:55,248 --> 01:45:58,775
And I'm sure the jury
is equally tired and hungry.

1665
01:45:58,885 --> 01:46:02,685
Tomorrow the defense takes over
and with expedition, prayer...

1666
01:46:02,789 --> 01:46:05,189
and a little self-discipline
on the part of counsel...

1667
01:46:05,292 --> 01:46:08,022
perhaps we can reach an end
by Saturday night.

1668
01:46:08,128 --> 01:46:10,926
Will you adjourn court?

1669
01:46:11,031 --> 01:46:12,760
Hear ye, hear ye, hear ye.

1670
01:46:12,866 --> 01:46:16,165
This court stands adjourned
until 9:00 tomorrow morning.

1671
01:46:57,511 --> 01:47:00,412
He's banged up a little, but there
doesn't seem to be anything else.

1672
01:47:00,514 --> 01:47:03,005
We'd like to watch him
for a day or so.

1673
01:47:03,116 --> 01:47:05,710
How much damage did he do?

1674
01:47:05,819 --> 01:47:08,379
Wrecked a gate and a barn door.

1675
01:47:08,488 --> 01:47:10,888
He hasn't got a driver's license.

1676
01:47:12,159 --> 01:47:15,788
He'll have to appear
in the J.P. Court when he's able...

1677
01:47:15,896 --> 01:47:17,693
the old fool.

1678
01:47:17,798 --> 01:47:19,891
Speak kindly of the dead.

1679
01:47:20,000 --> 01:47:22,059
Mind if I have a minute
with the corpse?

1680
01:47:22,169 --> 01:47:23,727
Sure.

1681
01:47:27,240 --> 01:47:30,368
Now, was it worth trying
to kill yourself...

1682
01:47:30,477 --> 01:47:33,571
for whatever it is
you've been up to?

1683
01:47:33,680 --> 01:47:35,580
How is the trial going?

1684
01:47:35,682 --> 01:47:38,810
I'm making a lot of noise
and Dancer's racking up all the points.

1685
01:47:38,919 --> 01:47:42,047
But come on.
Where have you been?

1686
01:47:42,155 --> 01:47:46,524
Quill hired Mary Pilant up north
of Sault St. Marie.

1687
01:47:46,626 --> 01:47:50,926
Struck me funny he'd go all the way up
there to hire somebody to work for him.

1688
01:47:51,031 --> 01:47:53,090
I've been up there nosing around.

1689
01:47:53,200 --> 01:47:55,327
Did you find anything useful?

1690
01:47:55,435 --> 01:47:58,427
Not until I looked up
her birth certificate.

1691
01:47:58,538 --> 01:48:02,201
Born Blind River, Ontario, 1934...

1692
01:48:02,309 --> 01:48:04,209
out of wedlock.

1693
01:48:04,311 --> 01:48:08,304
Mother was a waitress,
Simone Pilant.

1694
01:48:08,415 --> 01:48:12,613
Father was a lumberjack
named Barney Quill.

1695
01:48:20,126 --> 01:48:23,994
- I'd like to see Miss Mary Pilant.
- It's late, mister.

1696
01:48:24,097 --> 01:48:26,122
I know. This is important.

1697
01:48:26,233 --> 01:48:28,633
- Real important?
- Real important.

1698
01:48:33,573 --> 01:48:35,473
- Yes?
- Miss Pilant, sorry if I woke you.

1699
01:48:35,575 --> 01:48:37,975
There's a guy to see you.
Says it's real important.

1700
01:48:38,078 --> 01:48:39,978
- What's your...
- Paul Biegler.

1701
01:48:40,080 --> 01:48:42,981
- I don't wish to see him.
- Okay.

1702
01:48:44,217 --> 01:48:46,310
She said it's not important enough.

1703
01:48:46,419 --> 01:48:50,412
Call her back and tell her I mentioned
Blind River, Ontario.

1704
01:48:50,524 --> 01:48:52,754
I'll be in the bar.

1705
01:49:08,608 --> 01:49:10,508
Good evening, Alphonse.

1706
01:49:10,610 --> 01:49:12,840
Drinking or just snooping?

1707
01:49:12,946 --> 01:49:16,848
I think I'll try a little of both.
What do you say we start with a beer.

1708
01:49:22,155 --> 01:49:24,988
On the house.
And that's all you get... a beer.

1709
01:49:25,091 --> 01:49:27,059
No questions, no answers.

1710
01:49:27,160 --> 01:49:29,628
I'm just a lawyer
trying to do my job.

1711
01:49:29,729 --> 01:49:32,163
What are you so afraid of?

1712
01:49:35,201 --> 01:49:37,761
Let's sit over there, please.

1713
01:49:43,043 --> 01:49:47,104
Miss Pilant, I owe you an apology.
I was rough when I was here before.

1714
01:49:48,515 --> 01:49:50,506
I didn't know Barney Quill
was your father.

1715
01:49:50,617 --> 01:49:53,415
You didn't come here
just to apologize.

1716
01:49:53,520 --> 01:49:55,454
No, but the apology was part of it.

1717
01:49:55,555 --> 01:50:00,185
To tell you the truth, I was hoping
it would thaw you out a little bit.

1718
01:50:00,293 --> 01:50:04,423
All I want you to do is listen to me,
just for a few minutes.

1719
01:50:04,531 --> 01:50:09,332
I need some strong evidence to back up
Laura Manion's story about the rape.

1720
01:50:09,436 --> 01:50:12,928
The prosecution's gonna attack
that story pretty hard.

1721
01:50:13,039 --> 01:50:15,530
And if the jury thinks she's lying...

1722
01:50:15,642 --> 01:50:18,406
that could turn the decision
against Manion.

1723
01:50:18,511 --> 01:50:20,570
Isn't she lying?

1724
01:50:20,680 --> 01:50:23,444
Barney didn't do what she said he did.
He couldn't have.

1725
01:50:23,550 --> 01:50:27,714
- What did you know about your father?
- All I needed to know.

1726
01:50:27,821 --> 01:50:31,780
He took care of me and my mother
for as long as she lived.

1727
01:50:31,891 --> 01:50:35,156
He was always there
when I needed him.

1728
01:50:35,261 --> 01:50:37,821
That's what I know about my father,
Mr. Biegler.

1729
01:50:37,931 --> 01:50:40,126
Will that back up
Laura Manion's story?

1730
01:50:40,233 --> 01:50:43,168
I don't want to get at you,
hurt you.

1731
01:50:43,269 --> 01:50:45,794
I appreciate your affection
for your father.

1732
01:50:45,905 --> 01:50:51,434
But as a lawyer I've had to learn
that people aren't just good or bad...

1733
01:50:51,544 --> 01:50:53,842
but people are many things.

1734
01:50:53,947 --> 01:50:57,474
And I kind of have a feeling
Barney Quill was many things.

1735
01:50:57,584 --> 01:51:00,576
- I don't want to hear any more.
- No, please. Hear me out.

1736
01:51:00,687 --> 01:51:04,555
I believe that Barney told Al Paquette
what happened that night.

1737
01:51:04,658 --> 01:51:07,855
And he told him to go to this window
and wait for Manion.

1738
01:51:07,961 --> 01:51:12,694
Barney stayed behind the bar
next to a gun rack, just waiting.

1739
01:51:12,799 --> 01:51:16,200
Manion came in and fired
the minute he got inside that door...

1740
01:51:16,302 --> 01:51:18,998
and the first shot
went right through Barney's heart.

1741
01:51:19,105 --> 01:51:21,335
Now here's what I want you to do.

1742
01:51:21,441 --> 01:51:24,933
I want you to try to persuade Al
to come to the court...

1743
01:51:25,045 --> 01:51:29,072
as a defense witness and tell the court
what Barney told him that night...

1744
01:51:29,182 --> 01:51:32,049
that he raped and assaulted
Mrs. Manion.

1745
01:51:32,152 --> 01:51:36,816
Al wouldn't conceal a thing like that.
Why wouldn't he tell it if it were true?

1746
01:51:36,923 --> 01:51:40,120
I don't know.
But I know this.

1747
01:51:40,226 --> 01:51:43,787
Everybody loves something
or someone.

1748
01:51:43,897 --> 01:51:48,129
Me, I love fishing
and an old guy by the name of Parnell.

1749
01:51:48,234 --> 01:51:51,726
Manion loves his freedom.
He'd like to have a little more of it.

1750
01:51:51,838 --> 01:51:55,865
Barney loved you.
Maybe so does Al.

1751
01:51:55,975 --> 01:51:58,034
I wouldn't blame him.

1752
01:51:58,144 --> 01:52:01,841
But he doesn't want to hurt you or
for you to know the truth about Barney...

1753
01:52:01,948 --> 01:52:04,041
that he could be dangerous
and brutal.

1754
01:52:04,150 --> 01:52:08,177
Now, if you just ask Al...
if you just ask him right straight out.

1755
01:52:18,598 --> 01:52:22,193
Al, Mr. Biegler knows
that Barney was my father.

1756
01:52:23,803 --> 01:52:27,500
He thinks you know something
about the night my father was killed...

1757
01:52:27,607 --> 01:52:29,234
something you won't tell.

1758
01:52:29,342 --> 01:52:33,711
Lawyer, I told you once and I'll tell
you again... No questions, no answers.

1759
01:52:33,813 --> 01:52:35,371
Wait.

1760
01:52:37,517 --> 01:52:40,816
Did my father rape Mrs. Manion?

1761
01:52:40,920 --> 01:52:43,150
Barney wouldn't hurt a woman.

1762
01:52:44,758 --> 01:52:48,353
Is there any reason you wouldn't
tell me the truth about that?

1763
01:52:49,496 --> 01:52:51,361
What reason?

1764
01:52:57,337 --> 01:52:59,100
Anything else?

1765
01:53:00,039 --> 01:53:02,940
I'm going to leave a pass
for you and Al at the trial.

1766
01:53:03,042 --> 01:53:06,808
You might like to watch
Lt. Manion get convicted.

1767
01:53:06,913 --> 01:53:09,177
You going to spread it around
about Mary being Barney's kid?

1768
01:53:09,282 --> 01:53:12,945
No, I'm not going to spread it
around, Al. Thank you for the beer.

1769
01:53:13,052 --> 01:53:14,952
Good night, Miss Pilant.

1770
01:53:18,725 --> 01:53:21,592
All right. Let's get at
this rosary thing.

1771
01:53:21,694 --> 01:53:24,754
It's been testified that your wife
swore to you on a rosary...

1772
01:53:24,864 --> 01:53:27,298
that she'd been raped
by Barney Quill.

1773
01:53:27,400 --> 01:53:29,891
Did you ask your wife
to swear on a rosary?

1774
01:53:31,137 --> 01:53:34,231
My wife was hysterical.
She wasn't making much sense.

1775
01:53:34,340 --> 01:53:37,468
I thought if I asked her to take
an oath on a rosary...

1776
01:53:37,577 --> 01:53:40,478
it might serve to calm her,
make her think more clearly.

1777
01:53:40,580 --> 01:53:42,571
Did the rosary help?

1778
01:53:42,682 --> 01:53:45,173
She was able to tell me
in detail what had happened.

1779
01:53:45,285 --> 01:53:49,346
All right. Go on from there.
What did you do then, Lieutenant?

1780
01:53:49,455 --> 01:53:51,616
Well, l...

1781
01:53:51,724 --> 01:53:55,125
I had her lie on the bed,
and I got some cold cloths...

1782
01:53:55,228 --> 01:53:57,321
for her head.

1783
01:53:57,430 --> 01:54:01,059
And, uh...
Oh, yes. I gave her a drink of brandy.

1784
01:54:03,203 --> 01:54:06,639
After a while, she became calm,
seemed to go to sleep.

1785
01:54:07,907 --> 01:54:10,205
Then I went to the closet...

1786
01:54:10,310 --> 01:54:12,437
I got my gun,
and I loaded it.

1787
01:54:12,545 --> 01:54:15,480
Was it in your mind
to kill Barney Quill?

1788
01:54:15,582 --> 01:54:16,742
No.

1789
01:54:16,850 --> 01:54:19,842
Then why did you go to the closet
and get your gun and load it?

1790
01:54:19,953 --> 01:54:23,411
I knew I had to go to Quill's place.
I thought I might need it.

1791
01:54:23,523 --> 01:54:25,354
Why?

1792
01:54:25,458 --> 01:54:28,154
I knew Mr. Quill kept guns
behind the bar.

1793
01:54:28,261 --> 01:54:29,922
I was afraid he might shoot me.

1794
01:54:30,029 --> 01:54:31,929
Might shoot you if you did what?

1795
01:54:32,031 --> 01:54:34,932
What were you going to do?

1796
01:54:35,034 --> 01:54:37,161
I'm not sure.

1797
01:54:37,270 --> 01:54:39,932
I remember having some idea...

1798
01:54:40,039 --> 01:54:42,303
of finding him...

1799
01:54:42,408 --> 01:54:45,434
and holding him
while I call the police.

1800
01:54:45,545 --> 01:54:47,342
Well, that Mr. Whatshisname...

1801
01:54:47,447 --> 01:54:50,507
Mr. Lemon at the tourist court there,
he was a deputy sheriff.

1802
01:54:50,617 --> 01:54:53,017
Why didn't you get him
to go with you?

1803
01:54:53,119 --> 01:54:55,144
Maybe because he always
seemed to be just...

1804
01:54:55,255 --> 01:54:57,450
the old caretaker of the park.

1805
01:54:58,825 --> 01:55:02,283
Maybe because I wasn't thinking
about anything too clearly...

1806
01:55:02,395 --> 01:55:04,420
except finding Barney Quill.

1807
01:55:04,530 --> 01:55:08,227
Why didn't you go to a phone, call
the police before you went to the bar?

1808
01:55:08,334 --> 01:55:10,495
I don't know.

1809
01:55:10,603 --> 01:55:13,800
I was in sort of a daze.

1810
01:55:13,907 --> 01:55:16,808
It was a horrible thing to see
what had been done to my wife.

1811
01:55:16,910 --> 01:55:19,071
Now, you say you were in
sort of a daze.

1812
01:55:19,178 --> 01:55:22,841
When you got to the bar,
did you see that the bar was crowded?

1813
01:55:25,451 --> 01:55:28,249
I didn't see anyone at the bar...

1814
01:55:28,354 --> 01:55:31,152
except Barney Quill.

1815
01:55:31,257 --> 01:55:34,522
- He was the only person I saw.
- What was he doing?

1816
01:55:35,662 --> 01:55:39,291
I think he was just standing there
behind the bar.

1817
01:55:39,399 --> 01:55:43,563
Now, did he make a threatening move
to get a gun?

1818
01:55:43,670 --> 01:55:47,106
I don't know.
May have. I don't know.

1819
01:55:47,206 --> 01:55:50,141
All right. Now, you say
you went there to find him...

1820
01:55:50,243 --> 01:55:52,177
to hold him for the police.

1821
01:55:52,278 --> 01:55:54,178
Why did you shoot him?

1822
01:55:56,049 --> 01:55:58,279
I don't remember shooting him.

1823
01:55:59,385 --> 01:56:02,286
Now, when you left the bar,
do you remember Alphonse Paquette...

1824
01:56:02,388 --> 01:56:04,356
coming up to you
and stopping you and saying...

1825
01:56:04,457 --> 01:56:07,392
"You'd better not run away from this,"
and you replied...

1826
01:56:07,493 --> 01:56:09,620
"You want some too, buster?"

1827
01:56:09,729 --> 01:56:12,493
Remember that?

1828
01:56:12,598 --> 01:56:16,432
I seem to have a vague recollection
of somebody speaking to me...

1829
01:56:17,804 --> 01:56:21,240
but I don't remember what I said
or what was said to me.

1830
01:56:21,341 --> 01:56:24,242
When did you realize
that you'd shot Quill?

1831
01:56:27,013 --> 01:56:29,504
I was getting a drink of water.

1832
01:56:29,615 --> 01:56:32,675
I remember my throat was so dry
it hurt.

1833
01:56:34,120 --> 01:56:37,453
And when I put the glass down,
I saw the gun on the kitchen sink...

1834
01:56:37,557 --> 01:56:39,923
beside the tap.

1835
01:56:40,026 --> 01:56:41,926
I noticed the gun was empty.

1836
01:56:43,029 --> 01:56:45,827
Now, I'd like you to show
the court and jury...

1837
01:56:48,401 --> 01:56:50,892
just how you knew
this gun was empty.

1838
01:56:51,004 --> 01:56:53,495
Well, this gadget here...

1839
01:56:53,606 --> 01:56:57,372
when it sticks up,
you know the last round's been fired.

1840
01:56:59,579 --> 01:57:02,673
On the night of the shooting,
did you love your wife?

1841
01:57:02,782 --> 01:57:06,013
- Yes, sir.
- Do you still love her?

1842
01:57:09,489 --> 01:57:11,855
Very much.

1843
01:57:11,958 --> 01:57:14,085
The witness is yours, Mr. Dancer.

1844
01:57:17,296 --> 01:57:19,662
How many men have you killed?

1845
01:57:19,766 --> 01:57:22,098
Now, wait a minute!

1846
01:57:22,201 --> 01:57:25,534
Your Honor, a man's war record...
in Lt. Manion's case, a great record...

1847
01:57:25,638 --> 01:57:27,663
certainly shouldn't be used
against him.

1848
01:57:27,774 --> 01:57:30,709
I'm as patriotic as the next man...

1849
01:57:30,810 --> 01:57:33,335
but the simple truth is,
war can condition a man...

1850
01:57:33,446 --> 01:57:35,607
to killing other men.

1851
01:57:35,715 --> 01:57:38,309
I simply want to determine
how conditioned the lieutenant may be...

1852
01:57:38,418 --> 01:57:41,876
to the use of firearms
on other human beings.

1853
01:57:41,988 --> 01:57:45,856
I don't like the question, Mr. Biegler,
but I don't see how I can exclude it.

1854
01:57:45,958 --> 01:57:47,653
Let him answer.

1855
01:57:47,760 --> 01:57:51,423
I know I killed
at least four men in Korea...

1856
01:57:51,531 --> 01:57:53,431
three with a hand grenade...

1857
01:57:53,533 --> 01:57:55,763
and one with my service automatic.

1858
01:57:55,868 --> 01:57:59,668
I may have killed others.
A soldier doesn't always know.

1859
01:57:59,772 --> 01:58:02,002
Now, Lieutenant,
in these acts of killing...

1860
01:58:02,108 --> 01:58:05,737
did you ever have a lapse of memory such
as you had when you killed Barney Quill?

1861
01:58:05,845 --> 01:58:08,939
- No, sir.
- Did you ever have one during battle?

1862
01:58:09,048 --> 01:58:10,606
- No, sir.
- Were you ever submitted...

1863
01:58:10,716 --> 01:58:13,378
to a constant barrage,
constantly in a sweat for many hours...

1864
01:58:13,486 --> 01:58:15,750
- constantly under attack or attacking?
- Many times.

1865
01:58:15,855 --> 01:58:19,222
Were you ever treated for shell shock,
battle fatigue, neuroses or psychoses?

1866
01:58:19,325 --> 01:58:21,486
- No, sir.
- Did you ever experience...

1867
01:58:21,594 --> 01:58:24,188
any unusual mental state
during the war?

1868
01:58:24,297 --> 01:58:26,527
Well, I do remember having
one great urge.

1869
01:58:26,632 --> 01:58:30,466
- What was that?
- To get the hell out and go home.

1870
01:58:30,570 --> 01:58:33,130
You would do well to consider
the seriousness...

1871
01:58:33,239 --> 01:58:34,934
of the situation you're in.

1872
01:58:35,041 --> 01:58:38,033
- I'm sorry, Your Honor.
- I sympathize with the lieutenant.

1873
01:58:38,144 --> 01:58:42,137
I expect he has the same feeling
about getting out of jail.

1874
01:58:42,248 --> 01:58:44,409
But the main point here
is that at no time...

1875
01:58:44,517 --> 01:58:47,111
during your war service did you have
a record of mental disturbance.

1876
01:58:47,220 --> 01:58:49,415
You were always in complete possession
of your faculties.

1877
01:58:49,522 --> 01:58:51,888
Yes, sir. That's right.

1878
01:58:51,991 --> 01:58:54,789
- No more questions.
- No redirect, Your Honor.

1879
01:58:54,894 --> 01:58:57,328
Step down, please.
Call your next witness.

1880
01:58:57,430 --> 01:59:00,024
We call Laura Manion
to the stand.

1881
01:59:12,278 --> 01:59:15,679
- Up these stairs and to the right.
- Thanks.

1882
01:59:21,587 --> 01:59:24,215
How long after you told
your husband what had happened...

1883
01:59:24,323 --> 01:59:26,450
did he leave the trailer?

1884
01:59:26,559 --> 01:59:28,550
I don't know exactly.

1885
01:59:28,661 --> 01:59:30,322
Everything was kind of fuzzy.

1886
01:59:30,429 --> 01:59:33,091
I was faint,
and I laid down on the bed.

1887
01:59:33,199 --> 01:59:35,258
He sat beside me.

1888
01:59:35,368 --> 01:59:38,303
I vaguely remember
his getting up and going out.

1889
01:59:38,404 --> 01:59:40,998
I remember wondering
if he was going for a doctor...

1890
01:59:41,107 --> 01:59:43,302
and then he came back in.

1891
01:59:43,409 --> 01:59:45,969
It seemed like just a few seconds,
but it must have been longer.

1892
01:59:46,078 --> 01:59:48,672
I must've gone to sleep.

1893
01:59:48,781 --> 01:59:51,682
When he came back in,
he sat on the bed...

1894
01:59:51,784 --> 01:59:53,809
and he had a gun in his hand.

1895
01:59:53,920 --> 01:59:55,854
And I said, "What are you going to do?"

1896
01:59:57,023 --> 02:00:00,015
And he said,
"I think I've already done it.

1897
02:00:00,126 --> 02:00:02,321
I think I've killed Barney Quill."

1898
02:00:02,428 --> 02:00:05,920
Are you sure he didn't say,
"I've killed Barney Quill"?

1899
02:00:06,032 --> 02:00:08,523
No, I remember distinctly.

1900
02:00:08,634 --> 02:00:10,534
"I think I've killed Barney Quill."

1901
02:00:10,636 --> 02:00:12,604
Then what did you do?

1902
02:00:12,705 --> 02:00:16,971
I put my arms around him
and began to cry...

1903
02:00:17,076 --> 02:00:19,977
and I said,
"You'd better go to Mr. Lemon."

1904
02:00:20,079 --> 02:00:22,070
And my husband said,
"I forgot about that."

1905
02:00:22,181 --> 02:00:24,911
What did he mean?
Forgot about what?

1906
02:00:25,017 --> 02:00:28,509
He meant he'd forgotten
Mr. Lemon was a deputy sheriff.

1907
02:00:28,621 --> 02:00:31,385
And he said, "Yes,
I'll go turn myself in to Mr. Lemon."

1908
02:00:31,490 --> 02:00:32,821
Yes, I see.

1909
02:00:32,925 --> 02:00:36,224
Your Honor, I have no other
direct questions at this time.

1910
02:00:36,329 --> 02:00:39,321
But since I'm sure it's difficult
to visualize the part...

1911
02:00:39,432 --> 02:00:42,094
a little dog played on this night...

1912
02:00:42,201 --> 02:00:45,830
I should like a few minutes to show
the court this remarkable little animal.

1913
02:00:45,938 --> 02:00:47,929
Do the people object?

1914
02:00:48,040 --> 02:00:49,940
I'm sure that if we raise
an objection, Your Honor...

1915
02:00:50,042 --> 02:00:53,273
Mr. Biegler will declare that we are
haters of all small, furry animals.

1916
02:00:53,379 --> 02:00:57,338
A creature that cannot talk
will be a welcome relief.

1917
02:00:57,450 --> 02:00:59,441
Bring in the dog.

1918
02:00:59,552 --> 02:01:04,182
Thank you, sir. Will the deputy
bring in the dog, please?

1919
02:01:17,536 --> 02:01:19,731
You can put him right there.

1920
02:01:21,140 --> 02:01:23,233
Hey, Muff! Come on!

1921
02:01:24,710 --> 02:01:27,474
That's a boy.

1922
02:01:27,580 --> 02:01:31,038
And now I'll ask Mrs. Manion
to bring a flashlight for the dog.

1923
02:01:42,261 --> 02:01:46,664
I'll ask the court to notice
that the dog turned on the light.

1924
02:01:55,741 --> 02:01:59,006
It's easy to see that Muff doesn't know
who his enemies are.

1925
02:01:59,111 --> 02:02:01,272
- Remove the dog, please.
- Yes, sir.

1926
02:02:01,380 --> 02:02:04,042
- The witness will resume the stand.
- There we go, Muff.

1927
02:02:08,654 --> 02:02:11,748
May I congratulate you
on your well trained pet.

1928
02:02:11,857 --> 02:02:14,792
May I also say I'm pleased to see
you're not today...

1929
02:02:14,894 --> 02:02:17,158
hiding your lovely hair
under a hat.

1930
02:02:17,263 --> 02:02:20,960
Your Honor, is the assistant attorney
general from Lansing pitching woo...

1931
02:02:21,067 --> 02:02:24,798
- or is he going to cross-examine?
- Let's get on with it.

1932
02:02:24,904 --> 02:02:27,236
Mrs. Manion, what was your occupation
before you were married?

1933
02:02:27,340 --> 02:02:30,241
- Housewife.
- Then you've been married before?

1934
02:02:30,343 --> 02:02:34,712
- Yes, once.
- I suppose your first husband died?

1935
02:02:34,814 --> 02:02:36,042
No.

1936
02:02:36,148 --> 02:02:38,844
Did you divorce your first husband
to marry Lt. Manion?

1937
02:02:38,951 --> 02:02:40,646
Your Honor, if counsel wants
to know the grounds...

1938
02:02:40,753 --> 02:02:43,017
for Mrs. Manion's divorce,
let him ask that question.

1939
02:02:43,122 --> 02:02:44,851
What were the grounds
for divorce?

1940
02:02:44,957 --> 02:02:48,017
- Mental cruelty.
- Naturally. And how long after...

1941
02:02:48,127 --> 02:02:50,755
your divorce was it
that you married Lt. Manion?

1942
02:02:50,863 --> 02:02:52,592
I'm not sure.

1943
02:02:52,698 --> 02:02:55,758
May I refresh the witness' memory
for Mr. Dancer?

1944
02:02:55,868 --> 02:02:57,995
- By all means.
- I believe she told me...

1945
02:02:58,104 --> 02:03:01,335
that they were married
three days after the divorce.

1946
02:03:01,440 --> 02:03:03,704
Thank you, Mr. Biegler.
Is that correct, Mrs. Manion?

1947
02:03:05,144 --> 02:03:07,635
Then unless yours was
a whirlwind courtship...

1948
02:03:07,747 --> 02:03:09,840
you must have known Lt. Manion
before your divorce.

1949
02:03:09,949 --> 02:03:12,042
- Did you?
- Yes.

1950
02:03:12,151 --> 02:03:14,676
Mrs. Manion, what is your...

1951
02:03:14,787 --> 02:03:16,778
religious affiliation?

1952
02:03:16,889 --> 02:03:20,256
- I'm a Catholic.
- Catholic in good standing?

1953
02:03:20,359 --> 02:03:22,259
Well, no. The divorce, you know.

1954
02:03:22,361 --> 02:03:24,921
You mean you were excommunicated
because of the divorce and remarriage.

1955
02:03:25,030 --> 02:03:26,258
Yes.

1956
02:03:26,365 --> 02:03:29,061
Mrs. Manion, wouldn't you say
that a Catholic...

1957
02:03:29,168 --> 02:03:32,797
who can blithely ignore one of
the cardinal rules of her church...

1958
02:03:32,905 --> 02:03:36,432
could also easily ignore an oath
taken on one of its artifacts...

1959
02:03:36,542 --> 02:03:38,942
say, an oath taken on a rosary?

1960
02:03:40,513 --> 02:03:42,777
I don't think that's true.

1961
02:03:42,882 --> 02:03:46,249
Wouldn't you think there'd be some doubt
about the integrity of such a person?

1962
02:03:47,153 --> 02:03:49,053
I don't know.

1963
02:03:49,155 --> 02:03:51,589
All I know is the rosary
means something to me.

1964
02:03:51,690 --> 02:03:56,024
I see.
Well, I'll pass on to something else.

1965
02:03:56,128 --> 02:03:58,494
Mrs. Manion, you testified
that your husband...

1966
02:03:58,597 --> 02:04:00,827
came home late from his work
on the night of the shooting.

1967
02:04:00,933 --> 02:04:02,833
Were you a little angry
about his being late?

1968
02:04:02,935 --> 02:04:06,496
- I guess I was a little put out.
- Did you have an argument?

1969
02:04:06,605 --> 02:04:08,505
Not much. A little.

1970
02:04:08,607 --> 02:04:10,768
When you left the trailer
to go to the inn...

1971
02:04:10,876 --> 02:04:13,902
- did your husband know you were going?
- He was asleep.

1972
02:04:14,013 --> 02:04:16,174
Was part of your reason for going
without his knowledge...

1973
02:04:16,282 --> 02:04:18,477
because you were vexed?

1974
02:04:19,485 --> 02:04:23,114
Well, I'd been ironing all day,
and l...

1975
02:04:23,222 --> 02:04:25,713
- Yes, I guess that's true.
- Your Honor, the counsel...

1976
02:04:25,825 --> 02:04:28,123
has deliberately
cut off my view of the witness.

1977
02:04:28,227 --> 02:04:31,924
I'm sorry, Mr. Biegler. I wouldn't want
to interfere with your signals to her.

1978
02:04:32,031 --> 02:04:34,591
I object to the implication
I was signaling the witness.

1979
02:04:34,700 --> 02:04:37,692
This is the shabbiest courtroom trick
I've ever seen.

1980
02:04:37,803 --> 02:04:41,967
- You haven't lived, Mr. Biegler.
- I ask for a rule on my objection.

1981
02:04:42,074 --> 02:04:44,565
Mr. Dancer, will you be careful
not to place yourself...

1982
02:04:44,677 --> 02:04:46,668
between Mr. Biegler and his witness?

1983
02:04:46,779 --> 02:04:48,747
Of course, Your Honor.

1984
02:04:48,848 --> 02:04:51,646
- Anything else, Mr. Biegler?
- You do it once more...

1985
02:04:51,750 --> 02:04:56,084
I'll punch you all the way out
into the middle of Lake Superior.

1986
02:04:56,188 --> 02:04:58,349
Gentlemen. Gentlemen.

1987
02:04:58,457 --> 02:05:00,652
This rowing has got to stop.

1988
02:05:00,759 --> 02:05:04,695
The next one of you that speaks
out of turn will have me to deal with.

1989
02:05:04,797 --> 02:05:07,027
Get on with your cross-examination.

1990
02:05:07,132 --> 02:05:10,363
Would you have gone to the inn
if your husband had been awake?

1991
02:05:10,469 --> 02:05:13,870
- He probably would have gone with me.
- But would you have gone alone?

1992
02:05:13,973 --> 02:05:18,205
- Not if he didn't want me to.
- Would he have not wanted you to?

1993
02:05:18,310 --> 02:05:20,904
I'm not sure.
I don't know how to answer that.

1994
02:05:21,013 --> 02:05:23,607
Had you ever gone
to the Thunder Bay Inn, or...

1995
02:05:23,716 --> 02:05:26,617
elsewhere in Thunder Bay alone
at night?

1996
02:05:26,719 --> 02:05:29,950
- Yes, sometimes.
- Did your husband know you were going?

1997
02:05:30,055 --> 02:05:33,183
Not always.
He goes to sleep early...

1998
02:05:33,292 --> 02:05:36,022
and sometimes I'm restless.

1999
02:05:36,128 --> 02:05:39,928
- Where did you go on these occasions?
- I'd take a walk by the lake, or...

2000
02:05:40,032 --> 02:05:43,490
go into the bingo place,
maybe to the inn.

2001
02:05:43,602 --> 02:05:46,298
You ever go to meet another man?

2002
02:05:46,405 --> 02:05:48,373
No, I didn't.
I never did that.

2003
02:05:48,474 --> 02:05:51,341
You mean to say, Mrs. Manion,
a lovely women like yourself...

2004
02:05:51,443 --> 02:05:54,844
attractive to men, lonely, restless,
that you never once met...

2005
02:05:54,947 --> 02:05:57,939
Objection, Your Honor. The witness has
answered the question about other men.

2006
02:05:58,050 --> 02:06:00,814
The counsel is now making
a veiled suggestion to the jury.

2007
02:06:00,920 --> 02:06:02,911
I withdraw the question.

2008
02:06:03,022 --> 02:06:07,425
Mrs. Manion, on these occasional
excursions into the night...

2009
02:06:07,526 --> 02:06:10,086
did you always go
and return home alone?

2010
02:06:10,195 --> 02:06:11,628
Of course.

2011
02:06:11,730 --> 02:06:13,994
Mrs. Manion, you testified
that the reason you got...

2012
02:06:14,099 --> 02:06:17,728
into Barney Quill's car was because
you were afraid to go home alone.

2013
02:06:17,836 --> 02:06:19,804
Why were you so frightened
on this night?

2014
02:06:19,905 --> 02:06:24,342
I said that it was because he told me
bears had been seen around.

2015
02:06:24,443 --> 02:06:26,638
Was this the first time
you heard that...

2016
02:06:26,745 --> 02:06:28,736
bears came around Thunder Bay
for scraps?

2017
02:06:28,847 --> 02:06:31,611
- No.
- Had you seen the bears before?

2018
02:06:31,717 --> 02:06:32,775
Yes.

2019
02:06:32,885 --> 02:06:35,285
Oh, this was just the first time
you were afraid of them.

2020
02:06:35,387 --> 02:06:37,617
No, I was always afraid of them.

2021
02:06:37,723 --> 02:06:40,521
Oh, this was just the first time
you were enough afraid to allow...

2022
02:06:40,626 --> 02:06:43,186
a man to take you home
from one of your evening prowls.

2023
02:06:43,295 --> 02:06:46,958
Objection. Use of the word "prowls."
Meant to mislead the jury.

2024
02:06:47,066 --> 02:06:50,126
- Sustained.
- I apologize, Mrs. Manion.

2025
02:06:50,235 --> 02:06:52,999
I didn't mean to imply
that you were a huntress.

2026
02:06:53,105 --> 02:06:55,767
Was this the first time that
you were enough afraid to allow a man...

2027
02:06:55,874 --> 02:06:59,071
to take you home
from one of your evening walks?

2028
02:06:59,178 --> 02:07:02,011
Well, it wasn't just that.

2029
02:07:02,114 --> 02:07:04,014
- It was...
- Oh, come now, Mrs. Manion.

2030
02:07:04,116 --> 02:07:06,550
You should be able to answer that
straight off. That's a simple question.

2031
02:07:06,652 --> 02:07:09,314
Your Honor, how can the witness
answer straight off...

2032
02:07:09,421 --> 02:07:11,616
when the counsel keeps interrupting
the answer?

2033
02:07:11,724 --> 02:07:14,887
The witness seemed
a little slow to me, Mr. Biegler.

2034
02:07:14,994 --> 02:07:17,929
However, let her complete her answers
before you interrupt.

2035
02:07:18,030 --> 02:07:20,498
Of course, Your Honor. In any case,
Mr. Biegler's objection...

2036
02:07:20,599 --> 02:07:23,591
has given Mr. Manion sufficient time
to think of an answer to my question.

2037
02:07:23,702 --> 02:07:25,602
You've thought of one, haven't you?

2038
02:07:25,704 --> 02:07:29,140
What I was going to say was that
I didn't want to offend Mr. Quill...

2039
02:07:29,241 --> 02:07:32,438
by making him think that I was
afraid of him or didn't like him.

2040
02:07:32,544 --> 02:07:36,036
He's been very pleasant to my husband
and me when we'd been in his bar.

2041
02:07:36,148 --> 02:07:38,139
That's very good, Mrs. Manion.
Very good, indeed.

2042
02:07:38,250 --> 02:07:41,219
- Your Honor, please.
- The attorney for the people...

2043
02:07:41,320 --> 02:07:44,084
will reserve his comments
for the arguments.

2044
02:07:44,189 --> 02:07:47,386
I will ask you this question,
Mrs. Manion.

2045
02:07:47,493 --> 02:07:52,556
Was this the first time you had been
in Barney Quill's car at night?

2046
02:07:55,100 --> 02:07:58,467
Mrs. Manion, did you hear the question?

2047
02:07:58,570 --> 02:08:00,936
Yes, I heard.

2048
02:08:01,040 --> 02:08:03,941
Yes, it was the first time.

2049
02:08:04,043 --> 02:08:06,739
Would you raise your voice
a little, Mrs. Manion?

2050
02:08:06,845 --> 02:08:10,042
I said it was the first time.

2051
02:08:10,149 --> 02:08:12,242
Now, Mrs. Manion...

2052
02:08:12,351 --> 02:08:14,945
I'm quite concerned
about the lost panties.

2053
02:08:15,054 --> 02:08:18,023
Would you describe this article
of clothing to the courtroom?

2054
02:08:19,658 --> 02:08:22,525
They were nylon,
and had lace up the sides.

2055
02:08:22,628 --> 02:08:25,096
There was a label in them
of the place I got them...

2056
02:08:25,197 --> 02:08:28,724
- The Smart Shop in Phoenix, Arizona.
- What was the color of the panties?

2057
02:08:28,834 --> 02:08:30,768
- I believe, white.
- You believe?

2058
02:08:30,869 --> 02:08:33,167
I have white and pink.
They may have been pink.

2059
02:08:33,272 --> 02:08:34,967
You're not sure?
Haven't you checked your lingerie...

2060
02:08:35,074 --> 02:08:37,042
to see which pair of panties
is missing?

2061
02:08:37,142 --> 02:08:38,939
- No.
- When your husband came home late...

2062
02:08:39,044 --> 02:08:43,276
from work, and you had this little spat,
were you already dressed to go out?

2063
02:08:43,382 --> 02:08:45,282
- No.
- When did you dress?

2064
02:08:45,384 --> 02:08:47,113
After dinner, when he was asleep.

2065
02:08:47,219 --> 02:08:51,121
It's been stated here that you were
bare legged in the bar. Is that true?

2066
02:08:51,223 --> 02:08:53,851
In your anger at your husband and
your haste to get out of the trailer...

2067
02:08:53,959 --> 02:08:55,756
perhaps you didn't put on
any panties either.

2068
02:08:55,861 --> 02:08:58,796
Objection. Witness has already testified
of what she was wearing.

2069
02:08:58,897 --> 02:09:01,388
- Sustained.
- Do you always wear panties?

2070
02:09:01,500 --> 02:09:04,367
Your Honor, I object
to this line of questioning.

2071
02:09:04,470 --> 02:09:07,166
It's immaterial what Mrs. Manion
does all the time.

2072
02:09:07,272 --> 02:09:09,604
On the night she was attacked,
she was wearing panties...

2073
02:09:09,708 --> 02:09:12,006
and that's all we're concerned with.

2074
02:09:12,111 --> 02:09:16,047
Mrs. Manion seems a little bit uncertain
about the kind of panties she wore.

2075
02:09:16,148 --> 02:09:19,208
And since these panties have not been
found, I submit that it's possible...

2076
02:09:19,318 --> 02:09:21,786
she wasn't wearing any
and has forgotten.

2077
02:09:21,887 --> 02:09:26,153
- That's all I'm trying to get at.
- You may answer, Mrs. Manion.

2078
02:09:26,258 --> 02:09:29,421
You always wear panties?

2079
02:09:29,528 --> 02:09:31,359
No.

2080
02:09:31,463 --> 02:09:34,455
On what occasions don't you wear them?
When you go out alone at night?

2081
02:09:34,566 --> 02:09:38,468
No, no. Objection. He says he's going
after one thing and goes after another.

2082
02:09:38,570 --> 02:09:40,504
I'll sustain the objection.

2083
02:09:40,606 --> 02:09:44,201
Strike out the last two questions
in Mrs. Manion's answer.

2084
02:09:44,309 --> 02:09:48,746
Now, Mr. Dancer, get off the panties.
You've done enough damage.

2085
02:09:48,847 --> 02:09:50,838
Yes, Your Honor.

2086
02:09:50,949 --> 02:09:55,045
Mrs. Manion,
is your husband a jealous man?

2087
02:09:55,154 --> 02:09:58,385
- He loves me.
- I'm sure, but is he overly jealous?

2088
02:09:58,490 --> 02:10:01,288
Your Honor, how can the witness
answer that question?

2089
02:10:01,393 --> 02:10:03,327
What's the norm of jealousy?

2090
02:10:03,428 --> 02:10:06,454
Can you put your question
a little differently, Mr. Dancer?

2091
02:10:06,565 --> 02:10:09,398
- Has your husband struck you in a rage?
- No, Your Honor.

2092
02:10:09,501 --> 02:10:12,732
I think Mr. Dancer's fishing now.
What's the relevance of this question?

2093
02:10:12,838 --> 02:10:14,965
Your Honor, the shoe is squeezing
Mr. Biegler's foot.

2094
02:10:15,073 --> 02:10:16,973
In his own words,
this is not a high school debate.

2095
02:10:17,075 --> 02:10:19,236
This is a cross-examination
in a murder trial.

2096
02:10:19,344 --> 02:10:21,244
Proceed, Mr. Dancer.

2097
02:10:25,751 --> 02:10:28,948
Did you ever go out socially
in Thunder Bay?

2098
02:10:29,054 --> 02:10:30,885
Yes, a few times.

2099
02:10:30,989 --> 02:10:33,856
When your husband's outfit moved
to Thunder Bay, didn't Barney Quill...

2100
02:10:33,959 --> 02:10:37,417
throw a cocktail party
for the officers and their wives?

2101
02:10:37,529 --> 02:10:40,498
Didn't your husband strike a young
second lieutenant at this party?

2102
02:10:41,567 --> 02:10:44,730
There was a little scuffle.
It wasn't much.

2103
02:10:44,837 --> 02:10:48,102
- What was it about?
- I'm not sure I remember.

2104
02:10:48,207 --> 02:10:51,802
- Were you too drunk to remember?
- No, I was not.

2105
02:10:53,245 --> 02:10:55,270
I think it was because...

2106
02:10:55,380 --> 02:10:59,373
the lieutenant was cutting in too much
when I was dancing with my husband.

2107
02:10:59,484 --> 02:11:02,647
Shortly after on the verandah, didn't
your husband slap you hard enough...

2108
02:11:02,754 --> 02:11:04,949
so that you fell against the wall?

2109
02:11:07,526 --> 02:11:10,017
- He was drinking.
- Wasn't this a jealous rage?

2110
02:11:10,128 --> 02:11:14,292
- I don't know!
- Do you remember why he struck you?

2111
02:11:14,399 --> 02:11:18,699
Wasn't he enraged at you because he
thought you'd encouraged the young man?

2112
02:11:18,804 --> 02:11:21,705
- He might have thought so.
- There are witnesses to this affair.

2113
02:11:21,807 --> 02:11:24,401
I'll ask you again.
Wasn't this a jealous rage?

2114
02:11:24,509 --> 02:11:26,807
I guess you could call it that.

2115
02:11:28,313 --> 02:11:31,840
Now I'll ask you.

2116
02:11:31,950 --> 02:11:34,384
On the night of the shooting...

2117
02:11:34,486 --> 02:11:36,283
what did you swear?

2118
02:11:36,388 --> 02:11:38,583
What oath did you take on the rosary?

2119
02:11:39,825 --> 02:11:43,625
- It was about Barney Quill raping me.
- Why did you swear on the rosary...

2120
02:11:43,729 --> 02:11:45,959
that he raped you?

2121
02:11:46,064 --> 02:11:48,692
For the reason my husband said...
because I was hysterical!

2122
02:11:48,800 --> 02:11:51,394
That was the reason he gave for asking
you to swear. What was it for swearing?

2123
02:11:51,503 --> 02:11:53,437
- So he'd believe me.
- Why shouldn't he?

2124
02:11:53,538 --> 02:11:56,735
Objection! The reason for the use
of the rosary has been established.

2125
02:11:56,842 --> 02:11:58,434
These questions are immaterial.

2126
02:11:58,543 --> 02:12:02,138
No, I think I'll take
the answer, Mr. Biegler.

2127
02:12:02,247 --> 02:12:05,808
I'll ask you again, Mrs. Manion.
Why shouldn't he believe you?

2128
02:12:07,719 --> 02:12:09,846
Because I wasn't making much sense!

2129
02:12:09,955 --> 02:12:11,752
Did he think you'd lie
about a thing like that?

2130
02:12:11,857 --> 02:12:15,418
Objection, Your Honor! Lt. Manion had
already testified as to what he thought!

2131
02:12:15,527 --> 02:12:19,463
- Sustained.
- Did your husband strike you that night?

2132
02:12:19,564 --> 02:12:21,122
Did he hit you that night?

2133
02:12:24,102 --> 02:12:26,195
Well, he...

2134
02:12:26,305 --> 02:12:29,672
He may have slapped me
because I was hysterical.

2135
02:12:29,775 --> 02:12:32,243
Didn't you swear to a lie to keep him
from hitting you again?

2136
02:12:32,344 --> 02:12:34,244
No, I didn't! I did not!

2137
02:12:34,346 --> 02:12:37,543
Hadn't he already beaten you up when he
caught you coming home with Quill?

2138
02:12:37,649 --> 02:12:41,881
Objection! The witness has already
testified she was beaten by Quill!

2139
02:12:41,987 --> 02:12:44,114
Quiet. Quiet.

2140
02:12:44,222 --> 02:12:46,918
No more questions.

2141
02:12:47,025 --> 02:12:49,585
I think the witness
has had enough, Your Honor.

2142
02:12:49,695 --> 02:12:52,926
The witness may step down.
We'll recess for lunch.

2143
02:12:54,967 --> 02:12:56,867
Recess until 1:00.

2144
02:12:59,905 --> 02:13:01,805
I'm sorry, baby.
You were fine.

2145
02:13:35,307 --> 02:13:37,366
Dr. Smith.

2146
02:13:37,476 --> 02:13:40,138
I've come to meet you.
My name is...

2147
02:13:40,245 --> 02:13:42,975
- I'm sorry. You've been mistaken.
- Maybe I'm the one you're looking for.

2148
02:13:43,081 --> 02:13:45,049
Are you Mr. Biegler?

2149
02:13:45,150 --> 02:13:47,618
No, I'm his associate in the case.

2150
02:13:47,719 --> 02:13:50,483
- Don't tell me you're Dr. Smith.
- That's me.

2151
02:13:50,589 --> 02:13:52,784
The army psychiatrist?

2152
02:13:52,891 --> 02:13:55,155
Maybe you expected me
to be in uniform.

2153
02:13:55,260 --> 02:13:57,387
No.

2154
02:13:57,496 --> 02:13:59,987
I didn't expect anybody so young.

2155
02:14:00,098 --> 02:14:01,998
I'm 40.

2156
02:14:02,100 --> 02:14:05,035
I sort of hoped you'd...

2157
02:14:05,137 --> 02:14:07,537
have a beard and wear a monocle.

2158
02:14:07,639 --> 02:14:09,732
I see.

2159
02:14:09,841 --> 02:14:12,241
Is that better?

2160
02:14:12,344 --> 02:14:14,710
You're on the stand this afternoon.

2161
02:14:17,182 --> 02:14:19,946
Doctor, have you formed an opinion
as to Frederick Manion's...

2162
02:14:20,052 --> 02:14:22,987
mental and emotional state
at the time he killed Barney Quill?

2163
02:14:23,088 --> 02:14:24,715
- I have.
- And what is that opinion?

2164
02:14:24,823 --> 02:14:27,815
He was temporarily insane
at the time of the shooting.

2165
02:14:27,926 --> 02:14:30,121
At the time of the shooting,
do you believe he was able...

2166
02:14:30,228 --> 02:14:32,355
to distinguish right from wrong?

2167
02:14:32,464 --> 02:14:35,524
He may or may not have been.
It doesn't make too much difference.

2168
02:14:35,634 --> 02:14:38,694
Now, Doctor,
as clearly as you can...

2169
02:14:38,804 --> 02:14:42,365
will you explain
Frederick Manion's temporary insanity?

2170
02:14:42,474 --> 02:14:45,500
It is known as dissociative reaction...

2171
02:14:45,610 --> 02:14:47,942
a psychic shock which creates...

2172
02:14:48,046 --> 02:14:50,344
an almost overwhelming tension...

2173
02:14:50,449 --> 02:14:53,350
which the person in shock
must alleviate.

2174
02:14:53,452 --> 02:14:55,977
In Lt. Manion's case, a soldier...

2175
02:14:56,088 --> 02:14:58,921
it is only natural
that he would turn to action.

2176
02:14:59,024 --> 02:15:01,584
Only direct, simple action...

2177
02:15:01,693 --> 02:15:05,151
against Barney Quill would relieve
this unbearable tension.

2178
02:15:05,263 --> 02:15:08,892
This is not too uncommon. For example,
in combat, some of the more...

2179
02:15:09,000 --> 02:15:11,833
remarkable heroics take place
in this state of mind.

2180
02:15:11,937 --> 02:15:16,067
Is there another name for dissociative
reaction that we might recognize?

2181
02:15:16,174 --> 02:15:19,473
Yes, it has been known
as irresistible impulse.

2182
02:15:19,578 --> 02:15:22,809
Now, Doctor, a man in the grip
of irresistible impulse...

2183
02:15:22,914 --> 02:15:25,280
would he be likely to go
to his neighbor for advice...

2184
02:15:25,383 --> 02:15:28,079
or call up the police
to come to his aid?

2185
02:15:28,186 --> 02:15:31,019
- Completely incompatible.
- Yes, but our man...

2186
02:15:31,123 --> 02:15:33,751
was able to think of going
and taking out a gun...

2187
02:15:33,859 --> 02:15:36,225
and loading it before setting out
to find Quill.

2188
02:15:36,328 --> 02:15:40,731
That's his conscious mind working, but
he'd go even if a gun wasn't available.

2189
02:15:40,832 --> 02:15:44,461
How would a man look
in the grip of dissociative reaction?

2190
02:15:44,569 --> 02:15:48,596
He might appear to be deadly calm,
fiercely deliberate.

2191
02:15:48,707 --> 02:15:51,267
Mm-hmm.
Would you describe his behavior...

2192
02:15:51,376 --> 02:15:54,209
as being like a mailman
delivering the mail?

2193
02:15:54,312 --> 02:15:58,146
That's not bad. Like a mailman, he would
have a job to do, and he would do it.

2194
02:16:00,118 --> 02:16:02,586
- Your witness.
- Doctor...

2195
02:16:02,687 --> 02:16:05,121
did you find any psychosis
in Frederick Manion?

2196
02:16:05,223 --> 02:16:07,157
- I did not.
- Any neuroses?

2197
02:16:07,259 --> 02:16:09,193
I found no history of neuroses.

2198
02:16:09,294 --> 02:16:12,263
Any history of delusion?

2199
02:16:12,364 --> 02:16:14,264
- None.
- Loss of memory?

2200
02:16:14,366 --> 02:16:17,494
- Not before this instance.
- Did you find any history...

2201
02:16:17,602 --> 02:16:21,936
- Can you spot Mary Pilant?
- She didn't come back after lunch.

2202
02:16:22,040 --> 02:16:24,702
I think you'd better give up
on that one.

2203
02:16:24,809 --> 02:16:27,607
Doctor, you stated that the defendant
might or might not...

2204
02:16:27,712 --> 02:16:29,680
have been able to distinguish...

2205
02:16:29,781 --> 02:16:32,511
the difference between right and wrong,
but it wouldn't have made a difference.

2206
02:16:32,617 --> 02:16:34,744
- Am I right? Is that what you said?
- Approximately, yes.

2207
02:16:34,853 --> 02:16:36,787
Did you mean that at the time
of the shooting...

2208
02:16:36,888 --> 02:16:38,753
he could have known the difference
between right and wrong?

2209
02:16:38,857 --> 02:16:40,757
He might have, yes.

2210
02:16:40,859 --> 02:16:42,690
Dr. Smith...

2211
02:16:42,794 --> 02:16:45,729
if the defendant could have known
what he was doing...

2212
02:16:45,830 --> 02:16:48,264
and could have known it was wrong,
how can you come here...

2213
02:16:48,366 --> 02:16:50,459
and testify that he was legally insane?

2214
02:16:50,569 --> 02:16:53,037
I'm not saying
he was legally insane.

2215
02:16:53,138 --> 02:16:55,072
I'm saying that
in his mental condition...

2216
02:16:55,173 --> 02:16:57,698
it would not have made any difference
whether he knew right from wrong.

2217
02:16:57,809 --> 02:17:00,369
He would still have shot Quill.

2218
02:17:02,614 --> 02:17:06,448
Are you willing to rest your testimony
in this case on this opinion?

2219
02:17:06,551 --> 02:17:08,451
Yes, I am.

2220
02:17:09,854 --> 02:17:12,550
Your Honor, I'd like to ask
for a short recess.

2221
02:17:12,657 --> 02:17:16,593
The attorneys for the people would like
to meet with Mr. Biegler in chambers.

2222
02:17:17,495 --> 02:17:20,555
- Glad to oblige, Your Honor.
- Short recess.

2223
02:17:20,665 --> 02:17:22,633
The jury will remain.

2224
02:17:33,812 --> 02:17:35,905
Someday, I'm going to
horrify tradition...

2225
02:17:36,014 --> 02:17:38,505
and lay a dense, blue cloud...

2226
02:17:38,617 --> 02:17:41,711
of tobacco smoke
in that hallowed courtroom.

2227
02:17:41,820 --> 02:17:44,084
What's on your mind, Mr. Dancer?

2228
02:17:44,189 --> 02:17:46,521
Your Honor, in view of Dr. Smith's
testimony, I thought perhaps...

2229
02:17:46,625 --> 02:17:48,593
the defense might like
to change their plea.

2230
02:17:48,693 --> 02:17:51,491
- Change it to what?
- Guilty, of course.

2231
02:17:51,596 --> 02:17:53,530
No, we'll still go for broke.

2232
02:17:53,632 --> 02:17:56,192
Hell, Paulie, you know a guy's
not considered legally nuts...

2233
02:17:56,301 --> 02:17:58,326
in Michigan unless
he didn't know right from wrong.

2234
02:17:58,436 --> 02:18:02,896
- Why don't you get this over with?
- Your Honor, will you turn to page 486?

2235
02:18:03,008 --> 02:18:07,172
- What's that?
- Appears to be a law book, Mr. Lodwick.

2236
02:18:09,047 --> 02:18:11,072
Oh, I'm sorry, Your Honor.

2237
02:18:11,182 --> 02:18:13,707
I make those things
to help me think sometimes.

2238
02:18:13,818 --> 02:18:16,184
- For perch?
- No, it was for frog.

2239
02:18:16,288 --> 02:18:18,222
What case is he citing?

2240
02:18:18,323 --> 02:18:20,518
We gig frogs
in my part of the country.

2241
02:18:20,625 --> 02:18:23,321
It's the same up here.
I'm a trout man, myself...

2242
02:18:23,428 --> 02:18:25,419
but this is a new wrinkle
I'm gonna try.

2243
02:18:25,530 --> 02:18:29,432
They do it in the Bayou, down South.
The idea, they get a big, long pole...

2244
02:18:29,534 --> 02:18:31,832
and about a ten-pound line,
just sort of...

2245
02:18:31,936 --> 02:18:33,995
drift along a high bank
in a boat.

2246
02:18:34,105 --> 02:18:38,007
Then you see that big, old bullfrog
in the crevice...

2247
02:18:38,109 --> 02:18:40,202
and sort of float this along
in front of him.

2248
02:18:40,312 --> 02:18:43,042
Pop! That old tongue of his
snaps out, and...

2249
02:18:43,148 --> 02:18:45,116
You've got frog legs
for supper.

2250
02:18:45,216 --> 02:18:47,207
- I'll be darned.
- Why don't you keep it?

2251
02:18:47,319 --> 02:18:50,152
- Try it sometime.
- Thanks. I will.

2252
02:18:50,255 --> 02:18:52,189
Four eighty-six.

2253
02:18:53,425 --> 02:18:57,759
- What is it, Your Honor?
- People v. Durfee, 1886.

2254
02:18:57,862 --> 02:19:00,490
Looks like a precedent.

2255
02:19:00,598 --> 02:19:02,589
Would you like to read it?

2256
02:19:03,702 --> 02:19:07,297
No, thank you, Your Honor.
I think I recall the case.

2257
02:19:08,406 --> 02:19:11,239
We're hooked...

2258
02:19:11,343 --> 02:19:13,243
like the frog.

2259
02:19:16,247 --> 02:19:18,977
Dr. Harcourt, where did you receive
your university training?

2260
02:19:19,050 --> 02:19:20,984
Johns Hopkins in Baltimore, Maryland.

2261
02:19:21,086 --> 02:19:23,145
And where do you practice now?

2262
02:19:23,254 --> 02:19:26,849
I'm the medical superintendent of the
Bonder State Hospital for the Insane.

2263
02:19:26,958 --> 02:19:29,153
It's been stated here that...

2264
02:19:29,260 --> 02:19:32,161
dissociative reaction,
or irresistible impulse...

2265
02:19:32,263 --> 02:19:35,096
is not uncommon
among soldiers in combat.

2266
02:19:35,200 --> 02:19:37,930
- Do you agree with that statement?
- I do...

2267
02:19:38,036 --> 02:19:40,027
but not as it was put
by Dr. Smith.

2268
02:19:40,138 --> 02:19:43,904
- Where would you depart from Dr. Smith?
- Dissociative reaction...

2269
02:19:44,008 --> 02:19:47,739
is not something that comes out of
the blue and disappears as quickly.

2270
02:19:47,846 --> 02:19:52,078
It can only occur,
even among soldiers in combat...

2271
02:19:52,183 --> 02:19:56,119
if the individual has a psychoneurotic
condition of long standing.

2272
02:19:56,221 --> 02:19:59,884
It's been testified here that
a psychiatric exam of the defendant...

2273
02:19:59,991 --> 02:20:02,551
showed no evidence of neuroses...

2274
02:20:02,660 --> 02:20:04,992
and no history
of dissociative reaction.

2275
02:20:05,096 --> 02:20:07,064
You've further heard it testified...

2276
02:20:07,165 --> 02:20:09,156
that the defendant's behavior
on the night of the shooting...

2277
02:20:09,267 --> 02:20:11,827
was cool and direct.

2278
02:20:11,936 --> 02:20:15,497
As an observer,
do you remember this testimony?

2279
02:20:15,607 --> 02:20:18,838
From this, have you formed an opinion
about the defendant's sanity...

2280
02:20:18,943 --> 02:20:20,877
on the night of the shooting?

2281
02:20:20,979 --> 02:20:24,915
I'm of the opinion that he was in
possession of his faculties...

2282
02:20:25,016 --> 02:20:27,678
so that he was not dominated
by his unconscious mind.

2283
02:20:27,786 --> 02:20:31,620
In other words, he was not
in the grip of irresistible impulse.

2284
02:20:31,723 --> 02:20:33,953
- In my opinion, he was not.
- Thank you. Your witness.

2285
02:20:34,058 --> 02:20:38,051
Dr. Harcourt, psychiatry is an effort
to probe into the dark...

2286
02:20:38,163 --> 02:20:40,131
undiscovered world of the mind.

2287
02:20:40,231 --> 02:20:43,496
And in there, the world
might be round, it could be square.

2288
02:20:43,601 --> 02:20:47,298
Your opinion could be wrong, Dr. Smith's
could be right. Is that true?

2289
02:20:47,405 --> 02:20:50,067
I'd be a poor doctor
if I didn't agree with that.

2290
02:20:50,175 --> 02:20:53,576
But I believe my opinion
to be right.

2291
02:20:53,678 --> 02:20:56,078
Do you think you might've changed
your opinion...

2292
02:20:56,181 --> 02:20:58,809
if you'd examined the defendant
as Dr. Smith did?

2293
02:20:59,784 --> 02:21:02,014
- I don't believe so.
- But Dr. Smith's opinion...

2294
02:21:02,120 --> 02:21:04,213
was made under better circumstances,
wasn't it?

2295
02:21:04,322 --> 02:21:07,348
If you mean that he was able
to examine the man, yes.

2296
02:21:07,459 --> 02:21:10,860
- Yeah. Thank you, Doctor.
- That's all, Dr. Harcourt.

2297
02:21:10,962 --> 02:21:14,830
- Is there more rebuttal?
- We're over a barrel, Mitch.

2298
02:21:14,933 --> 02:21:17,527
We have to use him.

2299
02:21:17,635 --> 02:21:20,263
We call Duane Miller to the stand.

2300
02:21:20,371 --> 02:21:22,396
Will the sheriff please
bring in the witness?

2301
02:21:29,013 --> 02:21:31,379
What can he tell?

2302
02:21:31,483 --> 02:21:34,043
Nothing.

2303
02:21:34,152 --> 02:21:36,052
He can't tell anything.

2304
02:21:46,898 --> 02:21:50,265
Raise your right hand. Do you swear
the testimony you give in this cause...

2305
02:21:50,368 --> 02:21:53,337
shall be the truth, the whole truth, and
nothing but the truth, so help you God?

2306
02:21:53,438 --> 02:21:55,338
I do.

2307
02:21:57,308 --> 02:22:01,608
- State your name, please.
- Duane Miller. Most folks call me Duke.

2308
02:22:01,713 --> 02:22:03,613
Where do you presently reside?

2309
02:22:03,715 --> 02:22:05,774
Across the alley in the jail.

2310
02:22:05,884 --> 02:22:08,079
You know the defendant,
Frederick Manion?

2311
02:22:08,186 --> 02:22:11,019
Yeah, I got to know him in the past
few weeks. His cell's next to mine.

2312
02:22:11,122 --> 02:22:13,590
What was the last conversation
you had with the lieutenant?

2313
02:22:13,691 --> 02:22:17,286
Except for "hello" this morning,
the last time was last night.

2314
02:22:17,395 --> 02:22:21,058
- Did you discuss his trial last night?
- Yeah, some.

2315
02:22:21,165 --> 02:22:24,225
Would you tell the court what Lt. Manion
had to say about the trial?

2316
02:22:24,335 --> 02:22:27,827
Well, I said,
"Are things looking up, Lieutenant?"

2317
02:22:27,939 --> 02:22:30,840
And he said,
"I got it made, buster."

2318
02:22:30,942 --> 02:22:33,604
He said,
"I fooled my lawyer...

2319
02:22:33,711 --> 02:22:35,338
I fooled that head-shrinker...

2320
02:22:35,446 --> 02:22:38,006
and I'm gonna fool
that bunch of corn cobs on the jury."

2321
02:22:38,116 --> 02:22:41,779
Liar!
You're a lousy, stinkin' liar!

2322
02:22:43,221 --> 02:22:45,621
Take it easy, now.

2323
02:22:45,723 --> 02:22:48,590
I apologize for my client,
Your Honor.

2324
02:22:48,693 --> 02:22:52,390
Yet his outburst is almost excusable,
since the prosecution has seen fit...

2325
02:22:52,497 --> 02:22:56,092
to put a felon on the stand to testify
against an officer in the U.S. Army.

2326
02:22:56,200 --> 02:23:00,569
Your Honor, I don't know who's the
worse offender, Manion or his lawyer.

2327
02:23:00,672 --> 02:23:03,038
We're close to the end.

2328
02:23:03,141 --> 02:23:05,632
In the name of heaven,
let's have peace...

2329
02:23:05,743 --> 02:23:08,678
and courtesy
for these last few hours.

2330
02:23:08,780 --> 02:23:13,410
Mr. Dancer, you will continue
your interrogation without comment.

2331
02:23:13,518 --> 02:23:16,851
Mr. Biegler, you will not sound off
at every opportunity.

2332
02:23:16,955 --> 02:23:19,947
And the defendant will remain seated
in his chair and keep his mouth shut.

2333
02:23:20,058 --> 02:23:22,652
- Now go ahead.
- Mr. Miller...

2334
02:23:22,760 --> 02:23:25,456
are you certain
that Lt. Manion said...

2335
02:23:25,563 --> 02:23:27,758
"I've got it made, buster"?

2336
02:23:27,865 --> 02:23:30,629
- That's what he said.
- Did Lt. Manion say anything else?

2337
02:23:30,735 --> 02:23:33,203
Yes, sir. He said when he got out...

2338
02:23:33,304 --> 02:23:35,738
the first thing he was gonna do
was kick that bitch...

2339
02:23:35,840 --> 02:23:38,638
from here to kingdom come.

2340
02:23:38,743 --> 02:23:41,541
- To whom was he referring?
- To his wife.

2341
02:23:42,647 --> 02:23:44,137
Your witness.

2342
02:23:45,149 --> 02:23:47,549
- What are you in jail for, Mr. Miller?
- Arson.

2343
02:23:47,652 --> 02:23:49,643
I copped out,
and I'm waiting for a sentence.

2344
02:23:49,754 --> 02:23:51,745
How many other offenses
have you committed?

2345
02:23:51,856 --> 02:23:55,155
I was in reform school as a kid,
but that's all.

2346
02:23:55,259 --> 02:23:58,194
Your Honor, I'd like to see
this man's criminal record.

2347
02:23:58,296 --> 02:24:00,423
Do you have his record, Mr. Lodwick?

2348
02:24:00,531 --> 02:24:02,863
Yes, sir.

2349
02:24:02,967 --> 02:24:05,128
Here it is.

2350
02:24:07,438 --> 02:24:10,168
Your record shows you've been
in prison six times...

2351
02:24:10,274 --> 02:24:12,799
in three different states...

2352
02:24:12,910 --> 02:24:16,368
three times for arson, twice for assault
with a deadly weapon...

2353
02:24:16,481 --> 02:24:18,381
once for larceny.

2354
02:24:20,485 --> 02:24:23,420
Also shows you've done short stretches
in four city jails...

2355
02:24:23,521 --> 02:24:26,115
on charges of indecent exposure...

2356
02:24:26,224 --> 02:24:28,351
window-peeping, perjury...

2357
02:24:28,459 --> 02:24:31,360
and disorderly conduct.

2358
02:24:31,462 --> 02:24:34,260
Is this your true record?

2359
02:24:34,365 --> 02:24:36,128
Them things are never right.

2360
02:24:36,234 --> 02:24:38,532
How did you get the ear
of the prosecution...

2361
02:24:38,636 --> 02:24:41,935
in order to tell them about the
conversation you had with Lt. Manion?

2362
02:24:42,040 --> 02:24:45,032
- The D.A. Was taking us into his office.
- Taking who into his office?

2363
02:24:45,143 --> 02:24:48,442
- Us prisoners in the jail.
- All at once, or one at a time?

2364
02:24:48,546 --> 02:24:51,413
One at a time.
Him and that other lawyer...

2365
02:24:51,516 --> 02:24:55,475
took us to his office and asked us
questions about Lt. Manion.

2366
02:24:55,586 --> 02:24:58,851
Were you promised a lighter sentence
if you went on the witness stand?

2367
02:24:58,956 --> 02:25:02,050
- Your Honor, the people object to...
- Overruled. Answer the question.

2368
02:25:02,160 --> 02:25:05,652
- I wasn't promised anything.
- You thought it'd help your troubles...

2369
02:25:05,763 --> 02:25:08,095
if you dreamed up this story
to please the D.A.

2370
02:25:08,199 --> 02:25:11,066
- I didn't dream up nothin'.
- You're sure that's what Manion said?

2371
02:25:11,169 --> 02:25:14,263
- Yeah, I'm sure.
- As sure as you were about your record?

2372
02:25:14,372 --> 02:25:16,932
Well, I guess I kind of goofed
on that one.

2373
02:25:19,444 --> 02:25:21,935
Your Honor,
I don't feel I can dignify...

2374
02:25:22,046 --> 02:25:24,606
this creature with any more questions.

2375
02:25:24,716 --> 02:25:27,150
Take the witness away.

2376
02:25:27,285 --> 02:25:29,344
Would you like a conference
with your client?

2377
02:25:29,454 --> 02:25:32,582
I can see how the last witness
was quite a surprise.

2378
02:25:32,690 --> 02:25:34,954
No, Your Honor.
We don't need a conference.

2379
02:25:35,059 --> 02:25:37,619
I'll recall Lt. Manion
to the stand right now.

2380
02:25:45,870 --> 02:25:48,998
Now, you've heard the testimony
of this Miller.

2381
02:25:50,241 --> 02:25:52,709
- Is any part of it true?
- None.

2382
02:25:53,978 --> 02:25:58,210
Lieutenant, do you have any idea why he
might come here with a tale like that?

2383
02:25:58,316 --> 02:26:00,216
No, sir.

2384
02:26:01,753 --> 02:26:04,051
Have you ever talked with this man?

2385
02:26:05,923 --> 02:26:07,720
What did you talk about?

2386
02:26:09,794 --> 02:26:11,955
Nothing important.

2387
02:26:12,063 --> 02:26:15,624
Certainly, nothing about
my personal life or my feelings.

2388
02:26:15,733 --> 02:26:17,792
That's all I wanted to know.

2389
02:26:17,902 --> 02:26:20,530
Lt. Manion...

2390
02:26:20,638 --> 02:26:23,664
have you ever had
any sort of...

2391
02:26:23,775 --> 02:26:26,141
trouble with Miller?

2392
02:26:27,145 --> 02:26:29,875
I don't know. What do you mean?
An argument? Something like that?

2393
02:26:29,981 --> 02:26:33,781
Did you ever attack...
physically attack him?

2394
02:26:35,119 --> 02:26:37,587
Your lawyer can't answer
the question for you, Lieutenant.

2395
02:26:37,688 --> 02:26:42,318
- Did you ever physically attack Miller?
- I wouldn't call it an attack, exactly.

2396
02:26:42,426 --> 02:26:44,451
I pushed his head
against the bars one day.

2397
02:26:44,562 --> 02:26:47,656
- Why?
- He said something ugly about my wife.

2398
02:26:47,765 --> 02:26:51,360
Do you remember pushing or bumping
his head against the bars?

2399
02:26:51,469 --> 02:26:53,596
Sure. I just told you.

2400
02:26:53,704 --> 02:26:56,138
Then this was not
dissociative reaction.

2401
02:26:56,240 --> 02:26:58,765
The defendant isn't qualified
to answer that.

2402
02:26:58,876 --> 02:27:01,003
Lt. Manion...

2403
02:27:01,112 --> 02:27:03,444
wasn't your action against Barney Quill
much the same...

2404
02:27:03,548 --> 02:27:06,142
as your action against Miller
and against the lieutenant...

2405
02:27:06,250 --> 02:27:08,480
that you struck
at the cocktail party?

2406
02:27:08,586 --> 02:27:13,114
All in the heat of anger with a willful,
conscious desire to hurt or kill?

2407
02:27:13,224 --> 02:27:15,454
I don't remember
my action against Quill.

2408
02:27:16,694 --> 02:27:20,130
How long had you known that your wife
was running around with Barney Quill?

2409
02:27:21,566 --> 02:27:24,433
I never knew anything like that.

2410
02:27:24,535 --> 02:27:26,127
I trust my wife.

2411
02:27:27,405 --> 02:27:30,033
I suppose you just beat her up
occasionally for the fun of it.

2412
02:27:30,141 --> 02:27:33,406
Nothing has been established
to permit a question like that.

2413
02:27:33,511 --> 02:27:35,638
He keeps implying things
without getting to the point.

2414
02:27:35,746 --> 02:27:39,079
Let him ask the lieutenant,
did he ever beat his wife?

2415
02:27:39,183 --> 02:27:41,048
I'll sustain the objection.

2416
02:27:41,152 --> 02:27:43,677
Would you like to rephrase
your question, Mr. Dancer?

2417
02:27:45,389 --> 02:27:47,516
No thank you, Your Honor.

2418
02:27:47,625 --> 02:27:49,525
I've finished.

2419
02:27:49,627 --> 02:27:52,892
Then I'll ask him.
Did you, Lt. Manion...

2420
02:27:52,997 --> 02:27:56,125
ever beat your wife on the night
of the shooting or any other time?

2421
02:27:56,234 --> 02:27:58,168
- No, sir.
- Is there any doubt in your mind...

2422
02:27:58,269 --> 02:28:00,669
that Barney Quill raped Mrs. Manion?

2423
02:28:00,771 --> 02:28:02,671
- No, sir.
- That's all.

2424
02:28:02,773 --> 02:28:05,173
Step down, Lieutenant.

2425
02:28:10,281 --> 02:28:12,841
- We hurt?
- We're hurt bad.

2426
02:28:18,789 --> 02:28:22,555
Your Honor, I know time is pressing.
I don't want to ask for a recess.

2427
02:28:22,660 --> 02:28:24,594
I would like to leave
the courtroom for a moment.

2428
02:28:24,695 --> 02:28:27,255
If it's important,
we can be at ease for a minute.

2429
02:28:27,365 --> 02:28:29,697
Thank you, sir.

2430
02:28:29,800 --> 02:28:32,268
This is highly irregular,
Your Honor.

2431
02:28:32,370 --> 02:28:35,168
There's no reason to make
a federal case out of it.

2432
02:28:46,784 --> 02:28:50,220
Thank you very much, Your Honor.
We now have another rebuttal witness.

2433
02:28:50,321 --> 02:28:52,619
The defense calls Mary Pilant
to the stand.

2434
02:28:52,723 --> 02:28:54,816
We must protest this whole affair.

2435
02:28:54,926 --> 02:28:57,759
The noble defense attorney rushes out
to a secret conference...

2436
02:28:57,862 --> 02:29:00,831
and now the last-minute witness is being
brought dramatically down the aisle.

2437
02:29:00,932 --> 02:29:03,958
The whole thing has obviously been
rigged to unduly excite the jury.

2438
02:29:04,068 --> 02:29:06,536
It's another cornball trick.

2439
02:29:06,637 --> 02:29:09,902
Your Honor, I don't blame Mr. Dancer
for feeling put-upon.

2440
02:29:10,007 --> 02:29:12,976
I'm just a humble country lawyer
trying to do the best I can...

2441
02:29:13,077 --> 02:29:16,478
against this brilliant prosecutor
from the big city of Lansing.

2442
02:29:16,580 --> 02:29:18,946
Swear the witness.

2443
02:29:19,050 --> 02:29:22,850
Raise your right hand. Do you swear
the testimony you shall give...

2444
02:29:22,954 --> 02:29:26,754
shall be the truth, the whole truth, and
nothing but the truth, so help you God?

2445
02:29:26,857 --> 02:29:28,757
- I do.
- Sit down, please.

2446
02:29:31,929 --> 02:29:34,921
- Where do you live, Miss Pilant?
- At Thunder Bay Inn in Thunder Bay.

2447
02:29:35,032 --> 02:29:38,297
- And how long have you lived there?
- For two years.

2448
02:29:38,402 --> 02:29:41,371
- And what's your profession?
- I manage the inn.

2449
02:29:41,472 --> 02:29:46,102
Now, Miss Pilant, how is the laundry
handled at Thunder Bay Inn?

2450
02:29:46,210 --> 02:29:48,144
It's chuted down to the laundry room.

2451
02:29:48,245 --> 02:29:50,941
Where is the location of that chute
on the second floor?

2452
02:29:51,048 --> 02:29:54,575
- Between room 42 and 43.
- Who lives in those rooms?

2453
02:29:54,685 --> 02:29:58,348
I live in 42.
Mr. Quill lived in 43.

2454
02:29:58,456 --> 02:30:00,924
Would Mr. Quill,
coming up from the lobby...

2455
02:30:01,025 --> 02:30:05,724
have to pass by the mouth of that chute
on the way to his room?

2456
02:30:05,830 --> 02:30:10,324
Would it be very easy for him to drop
something into that chute as he passed?

2457
02:30:10,434 --> 02:30:14,302
Have you ever had occasion to go
down into the laundry at any time?

2458
02:30:14,405 --> 02:30:17,704
Yes. Part of my job is to sort
various pieces of laundry...

2459
02:30:17,808 --> 02:30:20,299
as they come out of
the wash-and-dry machine.

2460
02:30:20,411 --> 02:30:23,380
Would you tell the court what you found
among those pieces of laundry...

2461
02:30:23,481 --> 02:30:25,972
the day after Mr. Quill was killed?

2462
02:30:26,083 --> 02:30:28,313
I found a pair of women's panties.

2463
02:30:28,419 --> 02:30:31,388
- And what did you do with them?
- I threw them in the rag bin.

2464
02:30:31,489 --> 02:30:34,822
When did you learn the significance
of those panties?

2465
02:30:34,925 --> 02:30:37,860
Here.
This morning, in the courtroom.

2466
02:30:37,962 --> 02:30:40,522
And then you went home
and got them out of the rag bin?

2467
02:30:40,631 --> 02:30:42,599
Did you bring them with you?

2468
02:30:45,803 --> 02:30:49,136
I offer this article of lingerie...

2469
02:30:49,240 --> 02:30:51,572
as Exhibit Number One
for the defense.

2470
02:30:51,675 --> 02:30:55,907
They're white,
they have lace up the side...

2471
02:30:56,013 --> 02:30:58,277
and they're badly torn...

2472
02:30:58,382 --> 02:31:02,113
as if they've been ripped apart
by powerful hands.

2473
02:31:02,219 --> 02:31:04,153
The label reads...

2474
02:31:05,589 --> 02:31:08,183
"Smart Shop, Phoenix, Arizona."

2475
02:31:08,292 --> 02:31:11,625
If there is no objection, the exhibit
will be received in evidence.

2476
02:31:11,729 --> 02:31:14,823
- That's all, Miss Pilant.
- Do you ever talk to Mr. Lodwick...

2477
02:31:14,932 --> 02:31:16,866
about the death of Barney Quill?

2478
02:31:16,967 --> 02:31:19,902
He came to the hotel several times
after Mr. Quill was killed.

2479
02:31:20,004 --> 02:31:23,303
Did you tell Mr. Lodwick that you didn't
believe Barney Quill raped Mrs. Manion?

2480
02:31:23,407 --> 02:31:27,707
- Yes, I told him that.
- Did you ever talk to Mr. Biegler?

2481
02:31:27,812 --> 02:31:30,713
Was this also in connection
with the shooting of Quill?

2482
02:31:30,815 --> 02:31:33,545
Did you tell him you didn't believe
Barney Quill had raped Mrs. Manion?

2483
02:31:33,651 --> 02:31:35,881
- How many times did you talk to him?
- Twice.

2484
02:31:35,986 --> 02:31:38,181
- When was the last time?
- Last night.

2485
02:31:38,289 --> 02:31:40,587
And have you now changed your mind?
Do you now believe...

2486
02:31:40,691 --> 02:31:42,955
Barney Quill raped Mrs. Manion?

2487
02:31:43,060 --> 02:31:45,119
I don't know now.
I think he might have.

2488
02:31:45,229 --> 02:31:47,288
When did you change your mind?
Last night?

2489
02:31:47,398 --> 02:31:50,265
- No, it was here, this morning.
- When were you given the panties?

2490
02:31:50,367 --> 02:31:52,562
- Was that last night?
- Just wait a minute!

2491
02:31:52,670 --> 02:31:55,537
Use the proper form
of objection, Mr. Biegler.

2492
02:31:55,639 --> 02:31:59,632
On second thought, I don't object.
I'd like the jury to hear her answer.

2493
02:31:59,743 --> 02:32:02,234
- The witness may answer.
- No.

2494
02:32:02,346 --> 02:32:05,179
I was not given the panties last night
or at any other time.

2495
02:32:05,282 --> 02:32:08,115
- I found them exactly as I said.
- Do you know for a fact...

2496
02:32:08,219 --> 02:32:11,086
that Barney Quill dropped the panties
down the chute, or did you assume it?

2497
02:32:11,188 --> 02:32:13,122
- I assumed it.
- Had you thought maybe someone else...

2498
02:32:13,224 --> 02:32:16,682
might have put the panties there
who wanted them found in the laundry?

2499
02:32:16,794 --> 02:32:18,694
I hadn't thought of that.

2500
02:32:18,796 --> 02:32:22,630
And in the grip of what Mr. Biegler
might call irresistible impulse...

2501
02:32:22,733 --> 02:32:25,361
you rushed in here with the panties
because you wanted to crucify...

2502
02:32:25,469 --> 02:32:27,369
the dead Barney Quill,
isn't that true?

2503
02:32:27,471 --> 02:32:30,440
- No, I thought it was my duty...
- Your pride was hurt, wasn't it?

2504
02:32:30,541 --> 02:32:33,476
- I don't know what you mean.
- He's trying to confuse the witness.

2505
02:32:33,577 --> 02:32:36,045
Let him ask her a question
she can understand.

2506
02:32:36,147 --> 02:32:40,140
Yes, Mr. Dancer. I myself would like
to know what you're driving at.

2507
02:32:40,251 --> 02:32:43,584
Miss Pilant,
when you found the panties...

2508
02:32:43,687 --> 02:32:46,918
was your first thought that Barney Quill
might have raped Mrs. Manion...

2509
02:32:47,024 --> 02:32:50,926
or was it that he might have been
stepping out with Mrs. Manion?

2510
02:32:51,028 --> 02:32:53,087
I don't know what he means.

2511
02:32:53,197 --> 02:32:57,759
Mr. Dancer, once again I must ask you to
put straight questions to the witness.

2512
02:32:57,868 --> 02:33:01,304
Here is a straight question,
Your Honor.

2513
02:33:01,405 --> 02:33:04,067
Miss Pilant, are you
Barney Quill's mistress?

2514
02:33:04,175 --> 02:33:06,075
No. No, I was not!

2515
02:33:06,177 --> 02:33:08,168
It's common knowledge in Thunder Bay
you were living with Quill.

2516
02:33:08,279 --> 02:33:12,648
- That's not true. Barney Quill was...
- Was what, Miss Pilant?

2517
02:33:17,021 --> 02:33:19,581
Barney Quill was my father.

2518
02:33:31,035 --> 02:33:33,162
No more questions.

2519
02:33:33,270 --> 02:33:35,170
That's all for me.

2520
02:33:35,272 --> 02:33:38,173
The witness may step down.

2521
02:33:38,275 --> 02:33:40,869
We will recess for 15 minutes,
after which...

2522
02:33:40,978 --> 02:33:43,276
we will hear the closing arguments.

2523
02:33:43,380 --> 02:33:47,441
If possible, I would like to charge
the jury before nightfall.

2524
02:34:03,534 --> 02:34:05,968
Think they're gonna stay out all night?

2525
02:34:20,884 --> 02:34:23,444
Can't somebody say something?

2526
02:34:25,256 --> 02:34:27,747
What do you want me
to say, Maida, darling?

2527
02:34:27,858 --> 02:34:31,089
Tell me we're gonna win.

2528
02:34:31,195 --> 02:34:35,131
I'm counting on getting that
promissory note from the lieutenant.

2529
02:34:35,232 --> 02:34:39,396
I hope I can borrow some money on it.
I need a new typewriter.

2530
02:34:39,503 --> 02:34:43,701
Half the time, the "p" and the "f"
don't strike on mine.

2531
02:34:43,807 --> 02:34:46,401
"Party of the first part"
sometimes comes out...

2532
02:34:46,510 --> 02:34:49,001
"arty of the irst art."

2533
02:34:49,113 --> 02:34:51,843
Doesn't make sense.
It's embarrassing.

2534
02:34:51,949 --> 02:34:54,315
"Arty of the irst art"?

2535
02:34:54,418 --> 02:34:56,545
I kind of like that.

2536
02:34:56,654 --> 02:34:58,781
Has a ring to it.

2537
02:35:01,692 --> 02:35:04,388
Twelve people go off
into a room.

2538
02:35:05,896 --> 02:35:09,832
Twelve different minds,
twelve different hearts...

2539
02:35:09,933 --> 02:35:13,300
and twelve different walks of life.

2540
02:35:13,404 --> 02:35:17,306
Twelve sets of eyes, ears,
shapes and sizes.

2541
02:35:17,408 --> 02:35:20,309
And these twelve people...

2542
02:35:20,411 --> 02:35:23,505
are asked to judge
another human being...

2543
02:35:23,614 --> 02:35:27,050
as different from them
as they are from each other.

2544
02:35:27,151 --> 02:35:30,712
And in their judgment,
they must become of one mind.

2545
02:35:30,821 --> 02:35:33,551
Unanimous.

2546
02:35:33,657 --> 02:35:37,559
That's one of the miracles of man's
disorganized soul that they can do it.

2547
02:35:39,096 --> 02:35:41,189
And most instances,
do it right well.

2548
02:35:43,167 --> 02:35:46,034
God bless juries.

2549
02:35:47,271 --> 02:35:49,933
I don't know what I'd do
if I were on that jury.

2550
02:35:53,577 --> 02:35:55,477
I really don't know.

2551
02:35:56,914 --> 02:35:58,142
Do you?

2552
02:36:02,986 --> 02:36:04,886
I loved that, Paulie.

2553
02:36:04,988 --> 02:36:08,890
I loved that
"humble country lawyer" bit.

2554
02:36:08,992 --> 02:36:12,120
You had Mr. Dancer dancing.

2555
02:36:12,229 --> 02:36:14,129
I'm afraid he got in the last dance.

2556
02:36:14,231 --> 02:36:16,563
That's the best summary I've ever heard
in a courtroom.

2557
02:36:16,667 --> 02:36:19,568
I liked yours much better, Paulie.

2558
02:36:24,508 --> 02:36:27,341
Do you have to play that stuff?
Can't you play "Danny Boy"...

2559
02:36:27,444 --> 02:36:29,537
or "Sweet Isle of Innisfree"?

2560
02:36:43,627 --> 02:36:47,757
Paul Biegler's office.
Yes, sir. Right away.

2561
02:36:47,865 --> 02:36:49,765
They're ready.

2562
02:36:59,443 --> 02:37:01,604
Hey, sweetie.

2563
02:37:02,780 --> 02:37:05,442
Go on.

2564
02:37:05,549 --> 02:37:07,642
- The jury's coming in.
- Yeah, I heard.

2565
02:37:07,751 --> 02:37:10,720
You can tell my loving husband
I'll be waiting in the car.

2566
02:37:10,821 --> 02:37:13,915
- You're sure he's gonna come out?
- Oh, sure!

2567
02:37:14,024 --> 02:37:17,585
He's lucky.
Some people have all the luck.

2568
02:37:17,694 --> 02:37:22,256
You can tell him I'm waiting
to get kicked to kingdom come.

2569
02:37:22,366 --> 02:37:24,334
Oh! Hey, sweetie...

2570
02:37:24,435 --> 02:37:26,903
I have a souvenir for you.

2571
02:37:28,338 --> 02:37:30,329
You'd better keep that thing.

2572
02:37:30,441 --> 02:37:33,035
You might need it again sometime.
You never know.

2573
02:37:33,143 --> 02:37:35,270
No, you don't, do you?

2574
02:37:35,379 --> 02:37:37,609
Oh, I like you, Paulie.

2575
02:37:44,354 --> 02:37:48,154
I warn all those present not
to interrupt the taking of the verdict.

2576
02:37:48,258 --> 02:37:50,726
I will stop the proceedings
and clear the courtroom...

2577
02:37:50,828 --> 02:37:53,194
if there is any demonstration.

2578
02:38:02,139 --> 02:38:04,130
Proceed, Mr. Clerk.

2579
02:38:04,241 --> 02:38:06,801
Members of the jury,
have you agreed upon a verdict...

2580
02:38:06,910 --> 02:38:10,311
- and if so, who will speak for you?
- We have. I'm the foreman.

2581
02:38:10,414 --> 02:38:12,314
The defendant will rise.

2582
02:38:15,152 --> 02:38:17,450
- What is your verdict?
- We find the defendant...

2583
02:38:17,554 --> 02:38:19,988
not guilty by reason of insanity.

2584
02:38:25,662 --> 02:38:27,960
Maida gave you that promissory note,
didn't she?

2585
02:38:28,065 --> 02:38:30,625
Right here, ready to be signed
by our happy client.

2586
02:38:32,135 --> 02:38:35,764
You know, I used to think the world
looked better through a glass of whisky.

2587
02:38:35,873 --> 02:38:38,137
It doesn't.

2588
02:38:38,242 --> 02:38:40,972
I think I'll keep it this way.
Looks nice.

2589
02:38:42,212 --> 02:38:45,409
Well, I got one good thing
out of this case...

2590
02:38:45,516 --> 02:38:49,475
a new law partner,
if it's all right with him.

2591
02:38:49,586 --> 02:38:53,044
He'd be mighty proud to have his name
on a shingle with yours.

2592
02:39:23,253 --> 02:39:26,518
I guess you're looking for Lt. Manion,
aren't you, Mr. Biegler?

2593
02:39:26,623 --> 02:39:28,614
He gave me this note for you.

2594
02:39:30,193 --> 02:39:34,220
I felt real sorry for Mrs. Manion.
She was crying.

2595
02:39:34,331 --> 02:39:37,994
Left a mess, didn't they?
Well, we'd better get busy here.

2596
02:39:38,101 --> 02:39:42,037
"Dear Mr. Biegler,
so sorry that I had to leave suddenly.

2597
02:39:42,139 --> 02:39:45,074
I was seized
by an irresistible impulse.

2598
02:39:45,175 --> 02:39:47,735
Frederick Manion."

2599
02:39:47,844 --> 02:39:50,472
How in the world
are we gonna face Maida?

2600
02:39:52,082 --> 02:39:56,075
Gin. I knew there was
something wrong with that guy.

2601
02:39:56,186 --> 02:39:58,518
Never saw a gin drinker yet
you could trust.

2602
02:40:00,023 --> 02:40:03,015
Partner, what do you say
we go and see our first client?

2603
02:40:03,126 --> 02:40:05,321
- Who might that be?
- Mary Pilant.

2604
02:40:05,429 --> 02:40:07,920
We're gonna administer
Barney Quill's estate.

2605
02:40:08,031 --> 02:40:11,467
Now, that's what I call
poetic justice for everybody.

2606
02:40:32,001 --> 02:40:33,467
<i>{{{ the end }}} </i>